```
This will produce a 8x8 chessboard with the white and black pieces in the starting position, and the FEN notation of the board displayed below the board.

Note that you will need to have the `chess` package installed in your LaTeX distribution in order to use these commands.

Of course! I'd be happy to help you with your C++ program. To count the number of occurrences of a specific word in a text file line by line, you can use the following approach:

1. Open the text file using a file input stream.
2. Use a loop to read each line of the file into a string.
3. Use a regular expression to search for the specific word you want to count.
4. Use a variable to keep track of the number of occurrences of the word.
5. Print the number of occurrences at the end of the program.

Here's some sample C++ code that demonstrates this approach:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    // File name and word to count
    string filename = "example.txt";
    string wordToCount = "example";

    // Open the file
    ifstream file(filename);

    // Check if the file opened successfully
    if (!file) {
        cout << "Error: File could not be opened." << endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Initialize the word count to 0
    int wordCount = 0;

    // Read each line of the file
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        // Use a regular expression to search for the word
        std::regex wordPattern(wordToCount);
        std::smatch match;
        if (std::regex_search(line, match, wordPattern)) {
            // Increment the word count
            wordCount++;
        }
    }

    // Print the word count
    cout << "The word " << wordToCount << " appears " << wordCount << " times in the file." << endl;

    // Close the file
    file.close();

    return 0;
}
```
This program first opens the text file using a file input stream. It then reads each line of the file into a string using the `getline` function. For each line, it uses a regular expression to search for the specific word you want to count. If the word is found, it increments a variable to keep track of the number of occurrences. Finally, it prints the number of occurrences at the end of the program.

Note that this program assumes that the word you want to count is a single word, and that it does not appear in any other form (e.g., as a substring) in the text file. If you need to count multiple words or handle more complex cases, you may need to modify the regular expression or use a different approach.

