To improve the efficiency, you can use a more efficient partitioning method, such as the "hoare partition" or "introsort". These methods have a time complexity of O(n log n) on average, which is much faster than the O(n^2) time complexity of your current implementation.

Here's a hint: you can use a variable "pivot" to partition the array into two parts: one with elements less than the pivot, and another with elements greater than the pivot. You can then recursively call the quicksort function on the two partitions.

Here's some sample code to get you started:
```c
int partition(int nums[], int low, int high) {
    int pivot = nums[high];
    int i = low - 1;

    for (int j = low; j <= high - 1; j++) {
        if (nums[j] <= pivot) {
            i++;
            swap(nums[i], nums[j]);
        }
    }
    swap(nums[i + 1], nums[high]);
    return (i + 1);
}

void quicksort(int nums[], int low, int high) {
    if (low >= high) return; // base case
    int pivot = partition(nums, low, high); // partition the array into two parts
    quicksort(nums, low, pivot - 1); // recurse on left partition
    quicksort(nums, pivot + 1, high); // recurse on right partition
}
```
In the code above, the `partition` function partitions the array into two parts: one with elements less than the pivot, and another with elements greater than the pivot. The `quicksort` function then recursively calls itself on the two partitions.

Note that this is just one possible implementation of the quicksort algorithm. There are many variations and optimizations that you can explore to further improve the efficiency of the algorithm.

