The ConcurrentModificationException is occurring because you are iterating over the list `numbers` while simultaneously modifying it by removing elements. This is not allowed, as the list is being modified in the middle of the iteration.

To fix this, you can use a secondary list to store the elements that you want to keep, and then remove the elements that you don't want from the original list after you've finished iterating. Here's an example of how you could modify your code to avoid the ConcurrentModificationException:
```
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        numbers.add(3);
        numbers.add(4);
        numbers.add(5);

        List<Integer> keptNumbers = new ArrayList<>();

        for (Integer n : numbers) {
            if (n % 2 == 0) {
                keptNumbers.add(n);
            }
        }

        numbers.removeAll(keptNumbers);

        System.out.println(numbers);
    }
}
```
This code creates a new list called `keptNumbers` to store the elements that you want to keep, and then removes all of the elements that you don't want from the original list `numbers`. By removing all of the elements at once at the end of the iteration, you avoid the ConcurrentModificationException.

Alternatively, you could use the `Iterator` class to iterate over the list in a way that is safe from ConcurrentModificationExceptions. Here's an example of how you could do this:
```
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Iterator;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        numbers.add(3);
        numbers.add(4);
        numbers.add(5);

        Iterator<Integer> iterator = numbers.iterator();

        while (iterator.hasNext()) {
            Integer n = iterator.next();
            if (n % 2 == 0) {
                iterator.remove();
            }
        }

        System.out.println(numbers);
    }
}
```
This code uses the `iterator()` method to create an iterator over the list, and then uses the `hasNext()` method to check if there are any more elements in the list before removing them. By removing elements one at a time using the `remove()` method, you avoid the ConcurrentModificationException.

